A Study of BearWalk Waitng Time¶

Cheng Lin - Stat 222 Final Project¶

  1. Introduction

1.1 Background and Motivation¶

    Evening classes, research meetings, projects, etc. A lot of reasons can keep students on campus late at night. For safety concerns, many students ask BearWalk, a free night safety service, to get them where they need to go. The service starts after dark (6pm in fall and winter, 7pm in spring and 8pm in summer) and ends around 5:30 am. At the time of request, BearWalk will give the caller a prediction of waiting time. As a frequent BearWalk user, I am satisfied with the considerable service, except for its poor prediction of waiting time, especially in rush hours (12-3 am). After talking to Wyatt Lienhard, a community service program coordinator, I learnt that BearWalk currently makes prediction based on the average waiting time of the past hour. Skeptical of the efficiency of this method, I decide to use BeakWalk waiting time as the topic for my term project. Since the number of requests usually peaks around 2am, and waiting time and demand is correlated, I suspect that BearWalk waiting time follows a seasonal pattern.

    In this paper, I will find and fit models for the dynamics of BearWalk waiting time to answer the question: Can BearWalk waiting time be modeled better using a time series process? and how? This analysis may help improve CSO's waiting time prediction. It may also be valuable as a reference for BearWalk shifts arrangement in order to balance service waiting time.

1.2 Data¶

    I have to thank Carol Alfano and Wyatt Liehard for generously providing me BearWalk requests data of the fall semester. After summing up the number of students to be picked up and taking the average of actual waiting time for each hour, I got my final dataset: hourly record of average waiting time and number of costumers from 8/19/2013 to 12/15/2013 (119 full days). Since BearWalk is a night service and has no record from 6am to 5pm, I treat both average waiting time and customer counts during these hours as zeros.

2.2 Time Series Analysis¶

    Below is a time series plot of the hourly waiting time. The time series plot demonstrates a U-shape daily pattern. The pattern is supported intuitively: at 12am BearWalk is in the middle of its service, waiting time usually peaks at 1-3am, and keeps falling till the hour of 5am when the service ends. The service then begins around 6pm and waiting time increases in general as time moves towards midnight due to increasing demand.

2.2.2 ACF & Seasonality¶

    Why doesn't autogression fit? Our preliminary analysis on the daily pattern of waiting time may give us the answer. To confirm this 24 hour pattern. Let's look at the ACF and PACF of the time series. Indeed, ACF gives further support for a seasonal model as shown in the Figure below. The oscillation of ACF suggests seasonality with a period of 1 day, or 24 hours. Hence "failure to take seasonality into account" is the main reason of bad fit of the autogression model above.

In [15]:

    From ACF，it seems that there is a seasonal pattern of 24 hours in the waiting time. Let's take the seasonal difference with a lag of 24 hours, and see how the series of seasonal difference perform:

    The seasonal difference series looks stable. ACF plot of the seasonal differenced series suggests a seasonal MA(1) and the exponentially decaying PACF further supports it being an MA process. Hence I will set down (P,D,Q) = (0,0,1)

2.2.3 A better solution: SARIMAX Model¶

    Now I'd like to use a multiplicative seasonal ARIMA model, since it is unlikely that the true model incorporate auto correlation only at the seasonal lags. However, It seems to me that Python's statsmodels module can only handle SARIMA model. So I will use rmagic to call some R code here.

In [14]: 
%pylab inline
%load_ext rmagic 

Populating the interactive namespace from numpy and matplotlib
The rmagic extension is already loaded. To reload it, use:
  %reload_ext rmagic

    My first trials are Seasonal ARIMA and Seasonal Means Model. However, ACF of residuals rejects their independence in both models. A cosine and sine linear fit based on periodogram gives similar results.
    After the failure of fitting the data in SARIMA and seasonal means model, I decide to combine the two together. I use the hourly expected average waiting time as explanatory variables added to a SARIMA (p,d,q) ×(P,D,Q) model. The process is represented as follows:

\(\varphi_p(B)\Phi_P(B_s)W_t = \theta_q(B)\Theta_Q(B_s)e_t + \alpha \mu_t\)
\(W_t = \nabla^d\nabla^DY_t\)
\(\mu_t = \beta_i\) where i = t (mod 24)

     B represents the backwards shift operator, and \(e_t\) is a white noise process. \(W_t\) denotes the differenced series. \(\varphi_p\), \(\Phi_P\), \(\theta_q\), \(\Theta_Q\) are polynomials of order p, P, q, Q, each determined by its corresponding autoregressive or moving average terms. The 24 constants, β0,β1,... and β23 are the expected average waiting time of each hour given by Seasonal Means Model.

    We already know that (P,D,Q) = (0,0,1) from the section above. Set xreg =\(\mu_t\), and \(\beta_i\)'s are calculated using the code below from seasonal mean.

    Then I calculate BIC of various conbinations of (p,0,q) as an attempt to determine the optimal process. The BIC plot reaches its minimum value 18232.65 at (p,q) = (1,1), suggesting a SARIMA(1,0,1) ×(0,0,1). The BIC is significantly better than that of either pure SARIMA or seasonal means model.

2.2.4: Other Candidates¶

     Several other models also have performance comparable to that of SARIMAX. However, I find SARIMAX the easiest one to apply. For example, spurious correlation model returns that waiting time is led by number of requests with lag 0 and lag 1. Even though the result makes intuitive sense, the model is not practical because number of requests also requires prediction. Moreover, it is unlikely to be a one-way influence. Waiting time may in turn affects number of requests, so the model based on spurious correlation is not reliable. Another one I have looked into is STL decompositoin. Basically the model decomposes the time series in to three parts, short term daily trend, long term semester trend and errors. This is not a practical model either because the long term pattern is not externally valid. Fall semester is very different from Spring semester, and the pattern may change from year to year.

  1. Conclusion

     This Report attempts to capture and gain some insight in to BearWalk waiting time pattern using various seasonal models. BearWalk waiting time has obvious seasonal pattern with lag of 24 hours. However, the current prediction scheme used by BearWalk does not take this seasonality into account. While pure SARIMA model does not represent the series well, SARIMAX model using expected average waiting time as explanatory variables improves the fit significantly. Spurious correlation and STL decomposition models both have their strength in fitting waiting time, but they are not as useful as SARIMAX for practical perpose.

     There are many hidden variables for BearWalk that I have not been taken into account in this analysis, such as special regular users like Security Monitors, weather condition, school calendar.To better predict waiting time, I suggests further study in SARIMAX with more explanatory varibles mentioned above. Of course the problem can also be studied at a totally different angle, such as prediction based on location. However, this would require extra investment in monitoring devices and prediction based on times series is apparently more economical.

---------------------------------------End of Report ------------------------------------

 

Appendix

    The appendix includes methods that I mentioned above, but did not cover in detail in the report. Each of them has their draw backs compare to the ARIMAX model.

     SARIMA has large BIC and residuals do not look good.

     Seasonal means model also has large BIC and has problem with residuals.

     For spurious correlation model, CCF of prewhitened customer counts and waiting time demonstrates that waiting time is led by customer counts with lag 0 and lag 1. But the BIC is not as good as SARIMAX, moreover, because requests number itself would need prediction, the model will not really help with waiting time preidction.

    STL decomposition might even be better than SARIMAX in terms of performance. However, the seasonal trend is hard to quantify and may vary in different semesters. So this model is not externally valid.
